 {"id":"asupersync-akx.1.1","title":"Implement deterministic PRNG utility (no deps)","description":"# Deterministic PRNG Utility (No Dependencies)

## Purpose
The lab runtime and some combinators require deterministic tie-breaking and deterministic jitter. We must not introduce ambient randomness or rely on external heavy RNG crates unless justified.

This task introduces a tiny internal PRNG used *only* when determinism is required:
- lab scheduler tie-breaking among runnable tasks
- deterministic jitter/backoff (retry, hedge) in lab mode
- any future schedule exploration tooling

## Constraints
- No `rand` crate in core unless explicitly justified.
- Must be reproducible across platforms and Rust versions.
- Must be fast and simple.

## Plan-of-Record Design
### Algorithm
Use a small, well-known PRNG suitable for deterministic testing:
- `SplitMix64` as a seed expander and/or direct generator
- optionally layer `xoroshiro`-class generator if needed later

SplitMix64 is attractive because:
- trivial to implement
- good statistical properties for non-crypto use
- deterministic by construction

### API
```rust
pub struct DetRng {
    state: u64,
}

impl DetRng {
    pub fn new(seed: u64) -> Self;
    pub fn next_u64(&mut self) -> u64;

    /// Deterministic range selection.
    /// Must be unbiased (use rejection sampling) unless we explicitly accept modulo bias.
    pub fn gen_index(&mut self, len: usize) -> usize;

    /// Deterministic u32 convenience.
    pub fn next_u32(&mut self) -> u32;
}
```

### Unbiased `gen_index`
- Implement rejection sampling to avoid modulo bias for small domains.
- Document performance tradeoff and why it’s acceptable in lab scheduling.

## Acceptance Criteria
- Same seed yields identical sequences across runs.
- `gen_index(len)` never panics for `len > 0` and is deterministic.
- Unit tests cover:
  - golden vectors for a few seeds
  - determinism
  - range correctness

## Testing
- Unit test: generate first N outputs for a fixed seed and compare against hard-coded expected values.
- Property test: `gen_index(len) < len` for many seeds/lengths.

